{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778378539256,"sessionID":"ses_1f0683152ffeCYT9xjnCqVwnXn","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_gETEJbh2GnkLhnB2KShDQZQc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_34647572.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_34647572.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:34647572\n3: title: Differential use of p24 family members as cargo receptors for the transport of glycosylphosphatidylinositol-anchored proteins and Wnt1.\n4: authors:\n5: - Tashima Y\n6: - Hirata T\n7: - Maeda Y\n8: - Murakami Y\n9: - Kinoshita T\n10: journal: J Biochem\n11: year: '2022'\n12: doi: 10.1093/jb/mvab108\n13: keywords:\n14: - Animals\n15: - Carrier Proteins/metabolism\n16: - Endoplasmic Reticulum/metabolism\n17: - Glycosylphosphatidylinositols/metabolism\n18: - Golgi Apparatus/metabolism\n19: - Protein Transport\n20: content_type: abstract_only\n21: ---\n22: \n23: # Differential use of p24 family members as cargo receptors for the transport of glycosylphosphatidylinositol-anchored proteins and Wnt1.\n24: **Authors:** Tashima Y, Hirata T, Maeda Y, Murakami Y, Kinoshita T\n25: **Journal:** J Biochem (2022)\n26: **DOI:** [10.1093/jb/mvab108](https://doi.org/10.1093/jb/mvab108)\n27: \n28: ## Content\n29: \n30: 1. J Biochem. 2022 Jan 7;171(1):75-83. doi: 10.1093/jb/mvab108.\n31: \n32: Differential use of p24 family members as cargo receptors for the transport of \n33: glycosylphosphatidylinositol-anchored proteins and Wnt1.\n34: \n35: Tashima Y(1)(2), Hirata T(1)(3), Maeda Y(1), Murakami Y(1), Kinoshita T(1).\n36: \n37: Author information:\n38: (1)Research Institute for Microbial Diseases, and WPI Immunology Frontier \n39: Research Center, Osaka University, 3-1, Yamadaoka, Suita, Osaka 565-0871, Japan.\n40: (2)Department of Molecular and Cellular Biology, Nagoya University Graduate \n41: School of Medicine, Nagoya, Aichi 466-8550, Japan.\n42: (3)Center for Highly Advanced Integration of Nano and Life Sciences, Gifu \n43: University, Gifu 501-1193, Japan.\n44: \n45: Erratum in\n46:     J Biochem. 2022 Mar 31;171(4):469. doi: 10.1093/jb/mvac016.\n47: \n48: Complexes of p24 proteins act as cargo receptors for the transport of COPII \n49: vesicles from the endoplasmic reticulum (ER). The major cargos of p24 complexes \n50: are hydrophilic proteins tethered to the ER membrane via a covalently attached \n51: glycosylphosphatidylinositol (GPI) or fatty acid. Each p24 complex is known to \n52: contain members from all four p24 subfamilies (p24α, p24β, p24γ and p24δ). \n53: However, it remains unclear how the cargo specificities of p24 complexes are \n54: influenced by member stoichiometry. Here, we report the subunit compositions of \n55: mammalian p24 complexes involved in the transport of GPI-anchored proteins and \n56: Wnt1. We show that at least one p24α is required for the formation of p24 \n57: complexes and that a p24 complex consisting of p24α2, p24β1, p24γ2 and p24δ1 is \n58: required for the efficient transport of GPI-anchored proteins. On the other \n59: hand, a p24 complex containing p24α2, p24α3, p24β1, p24γ and p24δ1 is involved \n60: in the transport of Wnt1. Further, interactions between p24α2 and p24α3 are \n61: critical for Wnt1 transport. Thus, p24α and p24γ subfamily members are important \n62: for cargo selectivity. Lastly, our data fit with an octamer, rather than a \n63: tetramer, model of p24 complexes, where each complex consists of two proteins \n64: from each p24 subfamily.\n65: \n66: © The Author(s) 2021. Published by Oxford University Press on behalf of the \n67: Japanese Biochemical Society. All rights reserved.\n68: \n69: DOI: 10.1093/jb/mvab108\n70: PMID: 34647572 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n\n(End of file - total 70 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:34647572\ntitle: Differential use of p24 family members as cargo receptors for the transport of glycosylphosphatidylinositol-anchored proteins and Wnt1.\nauthors:\n- Tashima Y\n- Hirata T\n- Maeda Y\n- Murakami Y\n- Kinoshita T\njournal: J Biochem\nyear: '2022'\ndoi: 10.1093/jb/mvab108\nkeywords:\n- Animals\n- Carrier Proteins/metabolism\n- Endoplasmic Reticulum/metabolism\n- Glycosylphosphatidylinositols/metabolism\n- Golgi Apparatus/metabolism\n- Protein Transport\ncontent_type: abstract_only","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_34647572.md","time":{"start":1778378539231,"end":1778378539252}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0166a6a31a8344e90169ffe72b21f4819da3c6a345c4cc37f5"}},"id":"prt_e0f9f00ad001eM5YbiOagaAARn","sessionID":"ses_1f0683152ffeCYT9xjnCqVwnXn","messageID":"msg_e0f9ef0b0001yMbDpHLdocpRZC"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778378539257,"sessionID":"ses_1f0683152ffeCYT9xjnCqVwnXn","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_s6nesGWTG9pV5ruGQswrdcsC","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_27569046.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_27569046.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:27569046\n3: title: \"3D Structure and Interaction of p24β and p24δ Golgi Dynamics Domains: Implication for p24 Complex Formation and Cargo Transport.\"\n4: authors:\n5: - Nagae M\n6: - Hirata T\n7: - Morita-Matsumoto K\n8: - Theiler R\n9: - Fujita M\n10: - Kinoshita T\n11: - Yamaguchi Y\n12: journal: J Mol Biol\n13: year: '2016'\n14: doi: 10.1016/j.jmb.2016.08.023\n15: keywords:\n16: - Cell Line\n17: - \"Crystallography, X-Ray\"\n18: - Golgi Apparatus/metabolism\n19: - Humans\n20: - Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy\n21: - \"Membrane Proteins/chemistry, metabolism\"\n22: - \"Models, Molecular\"\n23: - Nucleocytoplasmic Transport Proteins\n24: - Protein Binding\n25: - Protein Conformation\n26: - Protein Interaction Mapping\n27: - Protein Multimerization\n28: - Protein Transport\n29: - Surface Plasmon Resonance\n30: - Vesicular Transport Proteins\n31: content_type: abstract_only\n32: ---\n33: \n34: # 3D Structure and Interaction of p24β and p24δ Golgi Dynamics Domains: Implication for p24 Complex Formation and Cargo Transport.\n35: **Authors:** Nagae M, Hirata T, Morita-Matsumoto K, Theiler R, Fujita M, Kinoshita T, Yamaguchi Y\n36: **Journal:** J Mol Biol (2016)\n37: **DOI:** [10.1016/j.jmb.2016.08.023](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jmb.2016.08.023)\n38: \n39: ## Content\n40: \n41: 1. J Mol Biol. 2016 Oct 9;428(20):4087-4099. doi: 10.1016/j.jmb.2016.08.023. Epub\n42:  2016 Aug 25.\n43: \n44: 3D Structure and Interaction of p24β and p24δ Golgi Dynamics Domains: \n45: Implication for p24 Complex Formation and Cargo Transport.\n46: \n47: Nagae M(1), Hirata T(2), Morita-Matsumoto K(1), Theiler R(2), Fujita M(3), \n48: Kinoshita T(2), Yamaguchi Y(4).\n49: \n50: Author information:\n51: (1)Structural Glycobiology Team, Systems Glycobiology Research Group, RIKEN-Max \n52: Planck Joint Research Center, RIKEN Global Research Cluster, 2-1 Hirosawa, Wako \n53: City, Saitama 351-0198, Japan.\n54: (2)Research Institute for Microbial Diseases and WPI Immunology Frontier \n55: Research Center, Osaka University, Suita, Osaka 565-0871, Japan.\n56: (3)Research Institute for Microbial Diseases and WPI Immunology Frontier \n57: Research Center, Osaka University, Suita, Osaka 565-0871, Japan; Key Laboratory \n58: of Carbohydrate Chemistry and Biotechnology, Ministry of Education, School of \n59: Biotechnology, Jiangnan University, Wuxi, Jiangsu 214122, China.\n60: (4)Structural Glycobiology Team, Systems Glycobiology Research Group, RIKEN-Max \n61: Planck Joint Research Center, RIKEN Global Research Cluster, 2-1 Hirosawa, Wako \n62: City, Saitama 351-0198, Japan. Electronic address: yyoshiki@riken.jp.\n63: \n64: The p24 family consists of four subfamilies (p24α, p24β, p24γ, and p24δ), and \n65: the proteins are thought to form hetero-oligomeric complexes for efficient \n66: transport of cargo proteins from the endoplasmic reticulum to the Golgi \n67: apparatus. The proteins possess a conserved luminal Golgi dynamics (GOLD) \n68: domain, whose functions are largely unknown. Here, we present structural and \n69: biochemical studies of p24β1 and p24δ1 GOLD domains. Use of GOLD domain-deleted \n70: mutants revealed that the GOLD domain of p24δ1 is required for proper p24 \n71: hetero-oligomeric complex formation and efficient transport of GPI-anchored \n72: proteins. The p24β1 and p24δ1 GOLD domains share a common β-sandwich fold with a \n73: characteristic intrasheet disulfide bond. The GOLD domain of p24δ1 crystallized \n74: as dimers, allowing the analysis of a homophilic interaction site. Surface \n75: plasmon resonance and solution NMR analyses revealed that p24β1 and p24δ1 GOLD \n76: domains interact weakly (Kd= ~10-4M). Bi-protein titration provided interaction \n77: site maps. We propose that the heterophilic interaction of p24 GOLD domains \n78: contributes to the formation of the p24 hetero-oligomeric complex and to \n79: efficient cargo transport.\n80: \n81: Copyright © 2016 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.\n82: \n83: DOI: 10.1016/j.jmb.2016.08.023\n84: PMID: 27569046 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n\n(End of file - total 84 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:27569046\ntitle: \"3D Structure and Interaction of p24β and p24δ Golgi Dynamics Domains: Implication for p24 Complex Formation and Cargo Transport.\"\nauthors:\n- Nagae M\n- Hirata T\n- Morita-Matsumoto K\n- Theiler R\n- Fujita M\n- Kinoshita T\n- Yamaguchi Y\njournal: J Mol Biol\nyear: '2016'\ndoi: 10.1016/j.jmb.2016.08.023\nkeywords:\n- Cell Line\n- \"Crystallography, X-Ray\"\n- Golgi Apparatus/metabolism\n- Humans\n- Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_27569046.md","time":{"start":1778378539235,"end":1778378539254}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0166a6a31a8344e90169ffe72b2208819d9f4e8a8b427b40a1"}},"id":"prt_e0f9f00e0001ClUUUDga64XNur","sessionID":"ses_1f0683152ffeCYT9xjnCqVwnXn","messageID":"msg_e0f9ef0b0001yMbDpHLdocpRZC"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778378539257,"sessionID":"ses_1f0683152ffeCYT9xjnCqVwnXn","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_oVsJbqGOVpEHyfC1bEcHqEeU","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_19566487.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_19566487.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:19566487\n3: title: The p24 family and selective transport processes at the ER-Golgi interface.\n4: authors:\n5: - Strating JR\n6: - Martens GJ\n7: journal: Biol Cell\n8: year: '2009'\n9: doi: 10.1042/BC20080233\n10: keywords:\n11: - Animals\n12: - Endoplasmic Reticulum/metabolism\n13: - Golgi Apparatus/metabolism\n14: - Humans\n15: - \"Membrane Proteins/chemistry, genetics, metabolism\"\n16: - Multigene Family\n17: - Protein Transport\n18: - Secretory Pathway\n19: content_type: abstract_only\n20: ---\n21: \n22: # The p24 family and selective transport processes at the ER-Golgi interface.\n23: **Authors:** Strating JR, Martens GJ\n24: **Journal:** Biol Cell (2009)\n25: **DOI:** [10.1042/BC20080233](https://doi.org/10.1042/BC20080233)\n26: \n27: ## Content\n28: \n29: 1. Biol Cell. 2009 Sep;101(9):495-509. doi: 10.1042/BC20080233.\n30: \n31: The p24 family and selective transport processes at the ER-Golgi interface.\n32: \n33: Strating JR(1), Martens GJ.\n34: \n35: Author information:\n36: (1)Department of Molecular Animal Physiology, Donders Centre for Neuroscience \n37: and Nijmegen Centre for Molecular Life Sciences (NCMLS), Faculty of Science, \n38: Radboud University, Nijmegen, The Netherlands.\n39: \n40: The secretory pathway is of vital importance for eukaryotic cells and has a \n41: pivotal role in the synthesis, sorting, processing and secretion of a large \n42: variety of bioactive molecules involved in intercellular communication. One of \n43: the key processes in the secretory pathway concerns the transport of cargo \n44: proteins from the ER (endoplasmic reticulum) to the Golgi. Type-I transmembrane \n45: proteins of approximately 24 kDa are abundantly present in the membranes of the \n46: early secretory pathway, and bind the COPI and COPII coat complexes that cover \n47: vesicles travelling between the membranes. These p24 proteins are thought to \n48: play an important role in the selective transport processes at the ER-Golgi \n49: interface, although their exact functioning is still obscure. One model proposes \n50: that p24 proteins couple cargo selection in the lumen with vesicle coat \n51: recruitment in the cytosol. Alternatively, p24 proteins may furnish \n52: subcompartments of the secretory pathway with the correct subsets of machinery \n53: proteins. Here we review the current knowledge of the p24 proteins and the \n54: various roles proposed for the p24 family members.\n55: \n56: DOI: 10.1042/BC20080233\n57: PMID: 19566487 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n\n(End of file - total 57 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:19566487\ntitle: The p24 family and selective transport processes at the ER-Golgi interface.\nauthors:\n- Strating JR\n- Martens GJ\njournal: Biol Cell\nyear: '2009'\ndoi: 10.1042/BC20080233\nkeywords:\n- Animals\n- Endoplasmic Reticulum/metabolism\n- Golgi Apparatus/metabolism\n- Humans\n- \"Membrane Proteins/chemistry, genetics, metabolism\"\n- Multigene Family\n- Protein Transport\n- Secretory Pathway\ncontent_type: abstract_only\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_19566487.md","time":{"start":1778378539237,"end":1778378539255}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0166a6a31a8344e90169ffe72b2210819d85c4e96f275259bb"}},"id":"prt_e0f9f00e4001UvHapDab1fyKsn","sessionID":"ses_1f0683152ffeCYT9xjnCqVwnXn","messageID":"msg_e0f9ef0b0001yMbDpHLdocpRZC"}}
