ch in NLM Catalog](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog?term=%22Cells%22%5BTitle+Abbreviation%5D)\n-   [Add to Search](#)\n\n. 2020 May 22;9(5):1295.\n\ndoi: 10.3390/cells9051295.\n\n# Dual Independent Roles of the p24 Complex in Selectivity of Secretory Cargo Export from the Endoplasmic Reticulum\n\n[Sergio Lopez](/?term=Lopez+S&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#full-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\")   [2](#full-view-affiliation-2 \"Instituto de Biomedicina de Sevilla (IBiS), Hospital Universitario Virgen del Rocío/CSIC/Universidad de Sevilla, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Ana Maria Perez-Linero](/?term=Perez-Linero+AM&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#full-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Javier Manzano-Lopez](/?term=Manzano-Lopez+J&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#full-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Susana Sabido-Bozo](/?term=Sabido-Bozo+S&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#full-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\")   [2](#full-view-affiliation-2 \"Instituto de Biomedicina de Sevilla (IBiS), Hospital Universitario Virgen del Rocío/CSIC/Universidad de Sevilla, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Alejandro Cortes-Gomez](/?term=Cortes-Gomez+A&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#full-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\")   [2](#full-view-affiliation-2 \"Instituto de Biomedicina de Sevilla (IBiS), Hospital Universitario Virgen del Rocío/CSIC/Universidad de Sevilla, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Sofia Rodriguez-Gallardo](/?term=Rodriguez-Gallardo+S&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#full-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\")   [2](#full-view-affiliation-2 \"Instituto de Biomedicina de Sevilla (IBiS), Hospital Universitario Virgen del Rocío/CSIC/Universidad de Sevilla, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Auxiliadora Aguilera-Romero](/?term=Aguilera-Romero+A&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#full-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\")   [2](#full-view-affiliation-2 \"Instituto de Biomedicina de Sevilla (IBiS), Hospital Universitario Virgen del Rocío/CSIC/Universidad de Sevilla, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Veit Goder](/?term=Goder+V&cauthor_id=32456004)  [3](#full-view-affiliation-3 \"Department of Genetics, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Manuel Muñiz](/?term=Mu%C3%B1iz+M&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#full-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\")   [2](#full-view-affiliation-2 \"Instituto de Biomedicina de Sevilla (IBiS), Hospital Universitario Virgen del Rocío/CSIC/Universidad de Sevilla, 41012 Seville, Spain.\")\n\nAffiliations Expand\n\n### Affiliations\n\n-   1 Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\n-   2 Instituto de Biomedicina de Sevilla (IBiS), Hospital Universitario Virgen del Rocío/CSIC/Universidad de Sevilla, 41012 Seville, Spain.\n-   3 Department of Genetics, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\n\n-   PMID: **32456004**\n-   PMCID: [PMC7291304](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7291304/)\n-   DOI: [10.3390/cells9051295](https://doi.org/10.3390/cells9051295)\n\nItem in Clipboard\n\n# Dual Independent Roles of the p24 Complex in Selectivity of Secretory Cargo Export from the Endoplasmic Reticulum\n\nSergio Lopez et al. Cells. 2020.\n\nShow details\n\nDisplay options\n\nDisplay options\n\nFormat Abstract PubMed PMID\n\nCells\n\nActions\n\n-   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Cells%22%5Bjour%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n-   [Search in NLM Catalog](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog?term=%22Cells%22%5BTitle+Abbreviation%5D)\n-   [Add to Search](#)\n\n. 2020 May 22;9(5):1295.\n\ndoi: 10.3390/cells9051295.\n\n### Authors\n\n[Sergio Lopez](/?term=Lopez+S&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\")   [2](#short-view-affiliation-2 \"Instituto de Biomedicina de Sevilla (IBiS), Hospital Universitario Virgen del Rocío/CSIC/Universidad de Sevilla, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Ana Maria Perez-Linero](/?term=Perez-Linero+AM&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Javier Manzano-Lopez](/?term=Manzano-Lopez+J&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Susana Sabido-Bozo](/?term=Sabido-Bozo+S&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\")   [2](#short-view-affiliation-2 \"Instituto de Biomedicina de Sevilla (IBiS), Hospital Universitario Virgen del Rocío/CSIC/Universidad de Sevilla, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Alejandro Cortes-Gomez](/?term=Cortes-Gomez+A&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\")   [2](#short-view-affiliation-2 \"Instituto de Biomedicina de Sevilla (IBiS), Hospital Universitario Virgen del Rocío/CSIC/Universidad de Sevilla, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Sofia Rodriguez-Gallardo](/?term=Rodriguez-Gallardo+S&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\")   [2](#short-view-affiliation-2 \"Instituto de Biomedicina de Sevilla (IBiS), Hospital Universitario Virgen del Rocío/CSIC/Universidad de Sevilla, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Auxiliadora Aguilera-Romero](/?term=Aguilera-Romero+A&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\")   [2](#short-view-affiliation-2 \"Instituto de Biomedicina de Sevilla (IBiS), Hospital Universitario Virgen del Rocío/CSIC/Universidad de Sevilla, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Veit Goder](/?term=Goder+V&cauthor_id=32456004)  [3](#short-view-affiliation-3 \"Department of Genetics, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\") , [Manuel Muñiz](/?term=Mu%C3%B1iz+M&cauthor_id=32456004)  [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\")   [2](#short-view-affiliation-2 \"Instituto de Biomedicina de Sevilla (IBiS), Hospital Universitario Virgen del Rocío/CSIC/Universidad de Sevilla, 41012 Seville, Spain.\")\n\n### Affiliations\n\n-   1 Department of Cell Biology, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\n-   2 Instituto de Biomedicina de Sevilla (IBiS), Hospital Universitario Virgen del Rocío/CSIC/Universidad de Sevilla, 41012 Seville, Spain.\n-   3 Department of Genetics, University of Seville, 41012 Seville, Spain.\n\n-   PMID: **32456004**\n-   PMCID: [PMC7291304](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7291304/)\n-   DOI: [10.3390/cells9051295](https://doi.org/10.3390/cells9051295)\n\nItem in Clipboard\n\nFull text links Cite\n\nDisplay options\n\nDisplay options\n\nFormat AbstractPubMedPMID\n\n## Abstract\n\nThe cellular mechanisms that ensure the selectivity and fidelity of secretory cargo protein transport from the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) to the Golgi are still not well understood. The p24 protein complex acts as a specific cargo receptor for GPI-anchored proteins by facilitating their ER exit through a specialized export pathway in yeast. In parallel, the p24 complex can also exit the ER using the general pathway that exports the rest of secretory proteins with their respective cargo receptors. Here, we show biochemically that the p24 complex associates at the ER with other cargo receptors in a COPII-dependent manner, forming high-molecular weight multireceptor complexes. Furthermore, live cell imaging analysis reveals that the p24 complex is required to retain in the ER secretory cargos when their specific receptors are absent. This requirement does not involve neither the unfolded protein response nor the retrograde transport from the Golgi. Our results suggest that, in addition to its role as a cargo receptor in the specialized GPI-anchored protein pathway, the p24 complex also plays an independent role in secretory cargo selectivity during its exit through the general ER export pathway, preventing the non-selective bulk flow of native secretory cargos. This mechanism would ensure receptor-regulated cargo transport, providing an additional layer of regulation of secretory cargo selectivity during ER export.\n\n**Keywords:** bulk flow; cargo receptor; endoplasmic reticulum; p24 complex; secretory cargo.\n\n[PubMed Disclaimer](/disclaimer/)\n\n## Conflict of interest statement\n\nThe authors declare no conflict of interest.\n\n## Figures\n\n [![Figure 1](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/52acb7957bc9/cells-09-01295-g001.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/738aa4c0e13a/cells-09-01295-g001.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 1\n\n**\n\nThe p24 complex interacts with…\n\n**\n\nFigure 1\n\n**\n\nThe p24 complex interacts with other cargo receptors at the ER membrane. ( **…**\n\n**Figure 1**\n\nThe p24 complex interacts with other cargo receptors at the ER membrane. (**A**) Coomassie staining of the p24 protein Emp24-TAP interactors. Cargo receptors (red) and p24 proteins (blue) that interact with Emp24-TAP (blue) are indicated. Enriched ER membrane fractions of wild-type yeast cells or cells expressing Emp24-TAP were isolated and solubilized with 1% digitonin. The extract was incubated with IgG-coupled magnetic beads and co-precipitated proteins were prepared and resolved by SDS-PAGE. Visualized bands and regions from the control reaction were subjected to in-gel digestion with trypsin and were analyzed by LC-MS/MS techniques (Figure S1, Tables S1 and S2). The star indicates the Emp24-TAP. (**B**) Co-immunoprecipitation assay between Erv14-mCi and other cargo receptors. Enriched ER membrane fractions of wild-type cells expressing Erv29-HA with or without expressing Erv14-mCi were solubilized, and immunoprecipitated (IP) with anti-GFP antibody, followed by immunoblotting with anti-Emp24, anti-HA, anti-Emp47, anti-Sec61 and anti-GFP antibodies. T represents a 0.5% of the solubilized input material.\n\n [![Figure 2](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/55791c7205d7/cells-09-01295-g002.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/1faf090c8d3a/cells-09-01295-g002.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 2\n\n**\n\nER cargo receptors associate into…\n\n**\n\nFigure 2\n\n**\n\nER cargo receptors associate into high molecular complexes in a COPII-dependent manner. ( **…**\n\n**Figure 2**\n\nER cargo receptors associate into high molecular complexes in a COPII-dependent manner. (**A**) Isolation of high weight molecular complexes. Enriched ER membrane fractions of wild-type cells expressing Erv14-mCi and Erv29-HA were solubilized with 1% digitonin and were fractionated by 5%–30% sucrose density gradient centrifugation. Fractions were collected from each gradient and directly analyzed by SDS-PAGE followed by immunoblotting with different antibodies. The asterisk represents a non-specific protein crossreacting with the anti-Emp47 antibody. (**B**) Fractions 9 and 10 were mixed and immunoprecipitated (IP) with anti-GFP antibody, followed by immunoblotting with anti-Emp24, anti-HA, anti-Emp47, anti-Sec61 and anti-GFP antibodies. The co-IP efficiency for Emp24, Erv29 and Emp47 was 0.8%, 4.1% and 2.5% respectively. T represents a 0.5% of the solubilized input material. (**C**) Physical interactions among ER cargo receptors depends on the COPII regulator Sec16. Enriched ER membrane fractions of wild-type and *sec16-2* mutant cells expressing Erv14-mCi, which were previously incubated at 37 °C, were solubilized, and immunoprecipitated (IP) with anti-GFP antibody, followed by immunoblotting with anti-Emp24 and anti-Emp47. T represents a 0.5% of the solubilized input material.\n\n [![Figure 3](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/4b5e2d2e5b01/cells-09-01295-g003.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/225bb0d94012/cells-09-01295-g003.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 3\n\n**\n\nThe p24 complex is required…\n\n**\n\nFigure 3\n\n**\n\nThe p24 complex is required for the ER retention of different secretory cargos…\n\n**Figure 3**\n\nThe p24 complex is required for the ER retention of different secretory cargos in the absence of their receptors. (**A**–**C**) Fluorescent live images of wild-type and different deletion strains expressing the secretory cargos Mid2-GFP (**A**), Gnt1-GFP (**B**) or CPY-GFP (**C**). The white arrow points out the perinuclear ER. Scale bar represents 5 µm. (**D**–**F**) Quantification of several micrographs described in (**A**,**B**) or (**C**). The graphs plot the average percentage of cells displaying perinuclear ER pattern. n, number of cells plotted ≥ 100. Different letters denote significant differences between strains (one-way ANOVA test, *p* ≤ 0.05).\n\n [![Figure 4](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/ae55f434d3c7/cells-09-01295-g004.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/11ff1d8d711d/cells-09-01295-g004.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 4\n\n**\n\nThe p24 complex is still…\n\n**\n\nFigure 4\n\n**\n\nThe p24 complex is still required for the ER export of GPI-APs in…\n\n**Figure 4**\n\nThe p24 complex is still required for the ER export of GPI-APs in the absence of other cargo receptors. (**A**) Fluorescent live images of wild-type and different deletion strains expressing Gas1-GFP or Cwp2-Venus. The white arrow points out the perinuclear ER. Scale bar represents 5 µm. (**B**,**C**) Quantification of several micrographs described in (**A**). The graphs plot the average percentage of cells displaying perinuclear ER pattern. n ≥ 100. Different letters denote significant differences between strains (one-way ANOVA test, *p* ≤ 0.05).\n\n [![Figure 5](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/31f0255edb1b/cells-09-01295-g005.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/8057bb28e689/cells-09-01295-g005.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 5\n\n**\n\nA secretory cargo retained at…\n\n**\n\nFigure 5\n\n**\n\nA secretory cargo retained at the ER by the p24 complex in the…\n\n**Figure 5**\n\nA secretory cargo retained at the ER by the p24 complex in the absence of its receptor is functional. (**A**) Budding patterns in wild-type (WT) and *erv14*Δ strains. Yeast cells were stained with calcofluor to visualize bud scars. Scale bar represents 5 µm. Wild-type and *emp24*Δ cells display the typical axial budding pattern whereas *erv14*Δ cells exhibit nonaxial budding patterns. However, the axial budding pattern is recovered in the *emp24*Δ*erv14*Δ double mutant cells. (**B**) Quantification of several micrographs described in (**A**). The graph plots the average percentage of cells displaying polarized scars. n ≥ 100. Different letters denote significant differences between strains (one-way ANOVA test, *p* ≤ 0.05).\n\n [![Figure 6](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/137558a41ba5/cells-09-01295-g006.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/664c03afddd5/cells-09-01295-g006.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 6\n\n**\n\nThe chronic activation of the…\n\n**\n\nFigure 6\n\n**\n\nThe chronic activation of the UPR does not cause the ER escape of…\n\n**Figure 6**\n\nThe chronic activation of the UPR does not cause the ER escape of a secretory cargo from the ER in the absence of its corresponding receptor. (**A**) Fluorescent live images of wild-type and different deletion strains expressing the Erv14 cargo GAP1-GFP mutated at ubiquitination sites (Gap1-ub-GFP) and without or with the plasmid pDN390 expressing spliced HAC1 mRNA (HAC1i) to chronically activate the UPR. The white arrow points out the perinuclear ER. Scale bar represents 5 µm. (**B**) Quantification of several micrographs described in (**A**). The graph plots the average percentage of cells displaying perinuclear ER pattern n ≥ 100. Different letters denote significant differences between strains (one-way ANOVA test, *p* ≤ 0.05).\n\n [![Figure 7](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/7de7050bc6fb/cells-09-01295-g007.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/32cbcd2da59e/cells-09-01295-g007.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 7\n\n**\n\nAn active COPI-dependent retrograde transport…\n\n**\n\nFigure 7\n\n**\n\nAn active COPI-dependent retrograde transport is not required for ER retention of a…\n\n**Figure 7**\n\nAn active COPI-dependent retrograde transport is not required for ER retention of a cargo expressed in the absence of its specific receptor. (**A**) Live images of wild-type, *erv14*Δ, *ret1-1* and *erv14*Δ *ret1-1* expressing Mid2-GFP at 37°C. Scale bar, 5 μm. (**B**) Quantification of several micrographs described in (**A**). The graph plots the average percentage of cells displaying Mid2-GFP in the ER. n ≥ 100. Different letters denote significant differences between strains (one-way ANOVA test, *p* ≤ 0.05).\n\n [![Figure 8](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/10533c7b4d06/cells-09-01295-g008.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/9df8/7291304/fc6a7f4b3d0e/cells-09-01295-g008.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 8\n\n**\n\nModel depicting the dual independent…\n\n**\n\nFigure 8\n\n**\n\nModel depicting the dual independent roles of the p24 complex in the selectivity…\n\n**Figure 8**\n\nModel depicting the dual independent roles of the p24 complex in the selectivity of cargo export from the ER. (**A**) In wild-type cells, GPI-APs are exported from the ER via their specialized COPII-dependent pathway by the p24 complex and non-GPI-APs are transported by their respective cargo receptors through the general COPII-dependent pathway. (**B**) In the absence of the p24 complex (*emp24*Δ cells), GPI-AP export is selectively blocked at the ER whereas non-GPI-APs are still efficiently exported by their respective receptors. (**C**) Deletion of a non-GPI cargo receptor, like Erv14, Erv26 or Erv29, leads to the selective ER retention of its specific cargos. (**D**) When one of these non-GPI cargo receptors and Emp24 are simultaneously mutated (double mutant cells), GPI-AP pathway is blocked whereas the specific non-GPI cargos of the mutated receptor can now escape from the ER by bulk flow. This effect indicates that the p24 complex, in addition to acting as a specific cargo receptor in the GPI-AP export pathway, also functions by preventing the non-selective ER exit by bulk flow of non-GPI cargos.\n\nAll figures (8)\n\n[See this image and copyright information in PMC](#)\n\n## References\n\n1.  1.  Gomez-Navarro N., Miller E. Protein sorting at the ER-Golgi interface. J. Cell Biol. 2016;215:769–778. doi: 10.1083/jcb.201610031. - [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1083/jcb.201610031) - [PMC](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5166505/) - [PubMed](/27903609/)\n2.  1.  Dancourt J., Barlowe C. Protein sorting receptors in the early secretory pathway. Annu. Rev. Biochem. 2010;79:777–802. doi: 10.1146/annurev-biochem-061608-091319. - [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-biochem-061608-091319) - [PubMed](/20533886/)\n3.  1.  D’Arcangelo J.G., Stahmer K.R., Miller E.A. Vesicle-mediated export from the ER: COPII coat function and regulation. Biochim. Biophys. Acta. 2013;1833:2464–2472. doi: 10.1016/j.bbamcr.2013.02.003. - [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.bbamcr.2013.02.003) - [PMC](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3676692/) - [PubMed](/23419775/)\n4.  1.  Geva Y., Schuldiner M. The back and forth of cargo exit from the endoplasmic reticulum. Curr. Biol. 2014;24:R130–R136. doi: 10.1016/j.cub.2013.12.008. - [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cub.2013.12.008) - [PubMed](/24502791/)\n5.  1.  Barlowe C., Helenius A. Cargo Capture and Bulk Flow in the Early Secretory Pathway. Annu. Rev. Cell Dev. Biol. 2016;32:197–222. doi: 10.1146/annurev-cellbio-111315-125016. - [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-cellbio-111315-125016) - [PubMed](/27298089/)\n\nShow all 57 references\n\n## Publication types\n\n-   Research Support, Non-U.S. Gov't\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Research+Support%2C+Non-U.S.+Gov%27t%22%5Bpt%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Research+Support%2C+Non-U.S.+Gov%27t)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n\n## MeSH terms\n\n-   COP-Coated Vesicles / metabolism\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22COP-Coated+Vesicles%2Fmetabolism%22%5BMeSH%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=COP-Coated+Vesicles)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   Endoplasmic Reticulum / metabolism\\*\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Endoplasmic+Reticulum%2Fmetabolism%22%5BMAJR%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Endoplasmic+Reticulum)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   Intracellular Membranes / metabolism\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Intracellular+Membranes%2Fmetabolism%22%5BMeSH%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Intracellular+Membranes)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   Models, Biological\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Models%2C+Biological%22%5BMeSH%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Models%2C+Biological)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   Multiprotein Complexes / metabolism\\*\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Multiprotein+Complexes%2Fmetabolism%22%5BMAJR%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Multiprotein+Complexes)\n    -   [Add